form provides little information about which part of speech they constitute. Thus non-inflecting parts of speech require criteria not based on morphology. The articles in this collection approach the classification issue from varying perspectives, applying construction grammar, descriptive linguistics, formal linguistics, and generative linguistics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGermanic languagesxGrammar, Comparative. 0aParts of speech. 4aFlexion. 4aMorphologie. 4aSyntax. 4aWortart. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aParts of speech.  ainflection.  amorphology.  asyntax.1 aAbraham, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGese, Helga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGünthner, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHohaus, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImo, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeer, Dorothee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNübling, Damaris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPittner, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Björn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothstein, Björn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchlief, Anne-Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSudhoff, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThieroff, Rolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08